==English==

===Etymology===
Possibly from French ''[[surgir]]'' < Old French ''[[surgir]]'' < Old Catalan ''[[surgir]]'' < Latin ''[[surgere]]'', to rush.

===Pronunciation===
*{{audio|en-us-surge.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*{{AHD|/sûrj/}}
*{{IPA|/sɝʤ/ (''US'') ''or'' /sɜːʤ/ (''UK'')}}
*{{SAMPA}} /<tt>s3`dZ</tt>/ (''US'') ''or'' /<tt>s3:dZ</tt>/ (''UK'')
*:Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ɜː(r)dʒ|-ɜː(r)dʒ]]

====Homophones====
* [[serge]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{nautical}} The [[swell]] or [[heave]] of the [[sea]]. (FM 55-501).
# A sudden [[rush]], [[flood]] or [[increase]].
#: ''He felt a '''surge''' of excitement.''
# A sudden [[electrical]] [[spike]] or [[increase]].
#: ''A power '''surge'''''

===Verb===
{{en-verb|surg|es}}

# {{intransitive}} To rush, flood, or increase suddenly.
#: ''Toaster sales '''surged''' last year.''
# {{cattag|transitive|nautical}} To [[slack off]] a [[line]].

